Bring a large #pot of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Dice @tomato{1} into ½-inch pieces.

Once water is boiling, add @linguine pasta{6%ounce} to #pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water (2 cups for 4 servings), then drain.

Pat @steelhead trout{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels and season all over with @salt{1%tsp} and @black pepper{1%tsp}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a large, preferably nonstick, #pan over medium-high heat. Add salmon, skin sides down, and cook until skin is crisp, ~{5-7%minutes}. Flip and cook until fish is opaque and cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate and tent with #foil to keep warm until ready to serve. Wipe out pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for salmon over medium heat. Add scallion whites; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Add tomato, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, @cream sauce base{4%ounce}, half the @Tuscan Heat Spice{½%tablespoon}, ⅓ cup reserved pasta cooking water, and a pinch of salt and pepper (all the Tuscan Heat Spice and ⅔ cup reserved pasta cooking water for 4 servings). Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce has thickened, ~{2-4%minutes}. Remove pan from heat.

Add @spinach{2.5%ounce} to pan with sauce; stir until just wilted. Add drained pasta and @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings); toss until pasta is coated and butter has melted.

> TIP: If needed, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time until pasta is thoroughly coated in sauce.

Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide pasta between #bowls. Top with salmon and garnish with scallion greens. Serve.